he arts. They are presented in many forms: essays in history and social science, poems, proverbs, lullabies, games, and short stories. Countries represented are Egypt, Jordan, Morocco, Tunisia, Israel/West Bank, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, Iran, Iraq, Syria, Sudan, Lebanon, Turkey, Yemen, and Afghanistan. This book complements Elizabeth Fernea's earlier works, Women and the Family in the Middle East and Middle Eastern Muslim Women Speak (coedited with Basima Bezirgan). Like them, it will be important reading for everyone interested in the Middle East and in women's and children's issues.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aChild rearingxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aChildrenzMiddle EastxSocial conditions. 0aIslamic education - Middle East. 0aIslamic educationzMiddle East. 0aParentingxReligious aspectsxIslam. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAlqudsi-Ghabra, Taghreed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaily, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelarbi, Aicha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBird, Jerine B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrink, Judy H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Douglas A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Susan Schaefer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDorsky, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoubleday, Veronica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEarly, Evelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElahi, Maryam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEyuboglu, Bedri R